\title{Frontend Design}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces with high design}

\p{This skill guides creation of distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces that avoid generic "AI slop" aesthetics. Implement real working code with exceptional attention to aesthetic details and creative choices.}

\p{The user provides frontend requirements: a component, page, application, or interface to build. They may include context about the purpose, audience, or technical constraints.}

\subtree{
\title{Design Thinking}
\p{Before coding, understand the context and commit to a BOLD aesthetic direction:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Purpose}: What problem does this interface solve? Who uses it?}
\li{\strong{Tone}: Pick an extreme: brutally minimal, maximalist chaos, retro-futuristic, organic/natural, luxury/refined, playful/toy-like, editorial/magazine, brutalist/raw, art deco/geometric, soft/pastel, industrial/utilitarian, etc.}
\li{\strong{Constraints}: Technical requirements (framework, performance, accessibility).}
\li{\strong{Differentiation}: What makes this UNFORGETTABLE? What's the one thing someone will remember?}
}

\p{\strong{CRITICAL}: Choose a clear conceptual direction and execute it with precision. Bold maximalism and refined minimalism both work - the key is intentionality, not intensity.}

\p{Then implement working code (HTML/CSS/JS, React, Vue, etc.) that is:}

\ul{
\li{Production-grade and functional}
\li{Visually striking and memorable}
\li{Cohesive with a clear aesthetic point-of-view}
\li{Meticulously refined in every detail}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Frontend Aesthetics Guidelines}
\p{Focus on:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Typography}: Choose fonts that are beautiful, unique, and interesting. Avoid generic fonts like Arial and Inter; opt instead for distinctive choices that elevate the frontend's aesthetics.}
\li{\strong{Color & Theme}: Commit to a cohesive aesthetic. Use CSS variables for consistency. Dominant colors with sharp accents outperform timid, evenly-distributed palettes.}
\li{\strong{Motion}: Use animations for effects and micro-interactions. Focus on high-impact moments: one well-orchestrated page load with staggered reveals creates more delight than scattered micro-interactions.}
\li{\strong{Spatial Composition}: Unexpected layouts. Asymmetry. Overlap. Diagonal flow. Grid-breaking elements. Generous negative space OR controlled density.}
\li{\strong{Backgrounds & Visual Details}: Create atmosphere and depth rather than defaulting to solid colors.}
}

\p{NEVER use generic AI-generated aesthetics like overused font families (Inter, Roboto, Arial), cliched color schemes (purple gradients on white), predictable layouts and component patterns.}

\p{Interpret creatively and make unexpected choices that feel genuinely designed for the context.}
}